"Notably, Teucrium and NYSE Arca filed the application under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, filing a 19b-4 form with the SEC. The already-approved bitcoin futures ETFs filed by other companies were under the Investment Company Act of 1940, which follows a slightly different regulatory pathway to approval. An approval under the Securities Act of 1933, under which Teucrium's filing falls, may potentially open the door for a spot bitcoin ETF, Bloomberg analyst James Seyffart said on Twitter earlier this year. Proponents of crypto ETFs have argued that "like situations must be treated alike," he said, citing an argument from crypto company Grayscale, which filed to convert its Grayscale Bitcoin Fund (GBTC) to an ETF." https://www.coindesk.com/policy/2022/04/06/sec-approves-teucriums-bitcoin-futures-etf/
https://seekingalpha.com/news/3812742-two-spot-bitcoin-etfs-rejected-by-sec

This is quite a hard one to judge, I ended up blending a few views:
American regulators are currently pushing against cryptocurrencies and satisfying regulators can take time, so this seems fairly unlikely.

Past Rulings So far, the SEC has ruled on 6 spot bitcoin ETF proposals and each time the agency denied the proposal because, in their view, the proposed ETF did not meet the requirement that a national securities exchange be “designed to prevent fraudulent and manipulative acts and practices” and “to protect investors and the public interest.”
Companies with denied applications for a spot ETF are suing. This is how the ETF in Canada came about. Tough to see a different outcome given a lot of western nations already have the spot ETF.
There was a crypto ETF already under consideration in 2021. Odds against are largely driven by possibility of overall market correction and unwillingness of regulators to allow a new asset

All 2021 and 2022-planned crypto ETFs for NASDAQ/NYSE are either based in crypto derivatives or stock in crypto mining companies. That might change, but probably not. Especially if MOASS happens Q1-Q2.
The SEC has been pretty clear about it's position, a general ETF is a lower bar than previous questions. I still don't think we will get there in 11 months, but am moving toward more uncertain.
ETF are being sold for every category
The Fed is still engaging in anti-competitive behavior against all challengers to its domination of the imaginary world of fiat currency.
Looks like the crowd is at the opposite of me (70 vs 30)... so I may be over optimistic. I'll move to 50/50, I still think it's in the cards, but time may be more of the issue
More and more people are moving towards or gave crypto. Once it gets past a critical mass the US Government won't want to stop it as the Democrats will fear losing young voters especially.

Coinbase, binance and several others are each hoping to become publicly traded and draw in the more conventional investors. While some feel that crypto currencies are funny money or a scheme, several countries have expressed interest in digitizing their currencies and with the advent of the metaverse and other prominent internet based stores of value, it would only make sense that the more user friendly centralized exchanges be listed as publicly traded.

https://finance.yahoo.com/news/sec-chair-gensler-reiterates-concern-over-investor-protection-despite-optimism-for-more-bitcoin-et-fs-172731741.html While there is a lot of time for this question to close, the commentary from the SEC has been the same over the past year(ever since Gensler took over). I have not seen any quantification from the SEC of what investor protection measures would it like to see before it concludes that Crypto ETF is safe. Reducing my estimate, will reconsider if the SEC gives an explanation or changes it stance

Governments and central banks will continue to crackdown down on cryptocurrencies (more or less directly and/or officially). Nasdaq and NYSE doesn't need to take any risks in that area, therefore they will stay on the sidelines.

Advantage of futures for the SEC is the exchanges they trade on are regulated, therefore a large driver of the approval of bitcoin ETF with exposure to futures not the underlying crypto. In order for the SEC to approve a pure bitcoin ETF it is likely the exchanges would need to become regulated - this is likely to require a large time window (>14m).

Still a while to go before more conclusive forecasts can be made. However we've recently had the future's ETF approved and it's been very popular. The mood of U.S regulators for the blue chip crypto's like BTC and ETH has shifted over the last few months. While DeFi is still under the spotlight I suspect BTC and ETH will be allowed to continue with institutional adoption. This lends itself towards an ETF being approved. Again, it's too early to call definitively, but I think this fact in of itself lends to a greater possibility of it incurring.

"The Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) punted on four bitcoin exchange-traded fund (ETF) applications today (Oct.3), shifting deadlines into late November and December. The SEC has a history of extensions when it comes to bitcoin ETFs. Many of the last wave of applications faced as many extensions as the Commission's mandate allows until finally receiving rejections." https://www.theblockcrypto.com/linked/119365/sec-rolls-decisions-on-four-bitcoin-etf-applications-to-end-of-2021

use case for crypto-ETFs: Any institution searching for exposure to crypto AND whose statutes barr it from buying crypto outright (or who decides against guarding their keys) AND who wants to diversify broader than publicly traded companies w/ BTC exposure.
